
Walter Kendall Myers, a former State Department official, was sentenced to life
in prison without parole Friday for his role in a 30-year conspiracy to provide
classified data to Cuba, the Justice Department said.

The man's wife, Gwendolyn Steingraber Myers, who was also charged in the
espionage case, was sentenced to 81 months in prison, a Justice Department
statement said.

The couple, arrested in June 2009, pleaded guilty last year to charges in
connected with "a nearly 30-year conspiracy to provide highly classified US
national defense information to the Republic of Cuba," the statement said.
